															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fieldstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1436137); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1436137&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250122" alt="fieldstone" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1436137)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fieldstone" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1436137); return false;" >fieldstone</a></span> <span class="odate time_1525012470 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Apr 2018 14:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3784468">
									

<p>According to the FBI's <a href="https://www.fbi.gov/file-repository/2017-ncic-missing-person-and-unidentified-person-statistics.pdf/view">National Crime Information Center</a>, 63,515 of the ~650,000 people reported missing in the USA in 2017 alone still haven't been found.</p>
<p>The most recent.<a href="https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;rct=j&amp;url=https://www.bjs.gov/content/pub/pdf/msp0114st.pdf&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiUooDh09_aAhXvmOAKHRGYDnIQFjAAegQIBxAB&amp;usg=AOvVaw3uEDcQDr1QrjZ9rZjHjeUE">Bureau of Justice Statistics</a> report I could find was 2014, which showed that 3,927 people were reported dead within the American prison system that year. However, all of their deaths are carefully documented, and in general the whole reason to put people in jail is so they'll be watched all the time. It would be much harder to cover up the disappearance of prisoners than to, say, set up Tindr accounts under fake identities so agents can take candidates on a couple dates to earn their trust, then get them in a car and drive them right over to the nearest Site for processing. Or just go get the person from their apartment under threat of force, if they fill some specific requirement like the one in the story.</p>
<p>The vast majority of the 2.3 million people incarcerated in the USA are there for relatively minor stuff such as drug possession - most of us would agree those aren't crimes that merit enslavement and horrible death, so it's not like taking people from jails is really much better from a moral standpoint anyway.</p>
<p>By the way, according to the BJS report, about 20 people per year actualy do disappear from the prison system and are never seen again, so that's unsettling.</p>

							</div>

								
