		<div class="post" id="post-3784907">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3784907)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3784907">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=274283&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250122" alt="ModernMajorGeneral" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=274283)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/modernmajorgeneral" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(274283); return false;" >ModernMajorGeneral</a></span> <span class="odate time_1525058422 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Apr 2018 03:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3784907">
									

<p>The majority (&gt;400,000) of the people reported missing are minors, though, and in almost everyone's writing and headcanon that excludes them from being D-class except in very specific circumstances.</p>
<p>I agree that there are still a large number of missing persons who are never found and would theoretically be able to be kidnapped by a fictional shadowy organisation for experiments without anyone noticing. However, they disproportionately belong to marginalised groups (homeless people, substance users, people with severe chronic mental illness, etc.), since it's an unfortunate aspect of society that people are more likely to expect them to go missing and they get investigated less.</p>
<p>The problem is that people rarely write these groups as kidnapped civilian D-class - the subjects of these stories are usually 'ordinary' middle-class people with stable jobs, lives and personal relationships, I suppose because to most authors they are more relatable. In every country in the world when someone like that disappears there is a massive media circus and people never stop talking about it. This tale in particular stretches that further as the disappeared people are from a small geographical area and mostly with similar backgrounds, which people would be even more likely to notice - though it serves a narrative purpose here and like I said I think this is good quality enough to overlook it.</p>
<p>As an aside, although applying consistent logic to the Foundation is a fool's errand, I personally think the D-class situation doesn't work with either prisoners or missing persons, and that any 'real' Foundation would have to use volunteers, who I imagine would be recruited and employed just like any other volunteers for a research study (albeit a shady one) and leave the Foundation's employ thinking they participated in a totally normal study, perhaps with the help of amnestics, with the truly 'disposable' personnel from prisoners or missing persons being reserved for SCPs that require a person to be fed to them regularly to save the world or whatever.</p>

							</div>

								
					
