    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-3785708">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-3785708">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3785708)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3785708">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="2303803"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1525131443 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Apr 2018 23:37</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3785708">
									

<p>You two made quite the interesting mini-discussion here, so thanks for all the information from both of you.</p>
<p>Mostly I'm inclined to agree that, yes, them getting away with kidnapping a few hundred people over a few days is unrealistic in the same way that most of what they get away with is unrealistic. That being said, I was thinking as I wrote that taking people from law enforcement and government backgrounds makes for a somewhat excusable disappearance reason (&quot;oh, the whole family knew they were in a risky field&quot;) but probably not to a degree of complete realism.</p>
<p>Of course, an implication I've always liked is that we don't <em>know</em> what's realistic or not in terms of who the Foundation can take off the radar without anyone noticing. They might do it so well that people get expunged from missing persons cases altogether.</p>

							</div>

								
					
